  "text": "in the limit of vanishing fermion masses. [CITATION_1] As argued in Ref. [9] , the decay rate is non-zero even in the limit of very large scalar masses. However, due to the factor of α EM Y 2 ψ /(12π), the decay rate to fermions is typically subdominant to the higgs and Z modes, even after summing over all possible fermion final states. One might wonder whether there could be an enhancement at moderate values of the scalar masses. Calculating the explicit tree-level decay rate for this mode to all orders in the scalar mass (while still working in the higgsino decoupling limit), the result in Eq. (4.14) is multiplied by a function f [m 2 φ /m 2 λ ]:",
